&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hypertext Markup Language&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;HTML&lt;/strong&gt; stands for &lt;strong&gt;Hypertext Markup Language&lt;/strong&gt;, which is the standard language used to create and design web pages.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is the backbone of any website, providing the basic structure and layout of web content.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;HTML uses &lt;strong&gt;tags&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;attributes&lt;/strong&gt; to define the elements on a page, such as headings, paragraphs, links, images, and more.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The latest version is &lt;strong&gt;HTML5&lt;/strong&gt;, which includes new elements and features for better multimedia support and improved performance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;HTML is commonly used alongside &lt;strong&gt;CSS&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;JavaScript&lt;/strong&gt; to create visually appealing and interactive websites.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

